1. The Psychological Pattern You Were Pointing To

When three actors exist in a decision system, a common human pattern emerges:

3 actors
2 align
1 disagrees

Humans tend to resolve this by forming a majority coalition.

That coalition may then:
	•	restrict the minority
	•	override the minority
	•	silence the minority
	•	remove the minority from the system

This is a well-studied group dynamic in psychology and organizational behavior.

It appears in:
	•	committees
	•	juries
	•	political bodies
	•	corporate boards
	•	social groups

The underlying mechanism is coalition formation. Two actors can form a stable alliance against the third.

⸻

2. Why This Matters in Decision Systems

In human groups, majority coalitions are often used because they are simple and fast.

But they also have well-known weaknesses:
	•	groupthink
	•	suppression of dissent
	•	premature consensus
	•	elimination of useful minority perspectives

This is why some decision systems intentionally include strong protections for dissent.

